The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes. The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation. Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority. Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database. A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency."}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-:12_18-0'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[18]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-:12-18', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockSubheader', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Examples'}, {'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'Examples'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The relational model gathers data together using information in the data. For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311". This would be done by searching selected datastores, or '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'tables'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Table_(database)', 'webpage_id': 5973540602338073572}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311". This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'indexes'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Database_index', 'webpage_id': 5973540601033242350}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'unique key'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unique_key', 'webpage_id': 5973540602444534328}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' (or primary key) of the record. If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys. Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-from_19-0'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[19]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-from-19', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Relational databases do not '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'inherently'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': " contain the idea of fixed relationships between records. Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data. For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called "}, {'_': 'TextFixed', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'userpk'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', which contains the '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'primary key'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primary_key', 'webpage_id': 5973540601609264594}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' of the user record it is associated with. In order to link users and their email addresses, the system first looks up the selected user records primary keys, looks for those keys in the '}, {'_': 'TextFixed', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'userpk'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' column in the email table (or, more likely, an index of them), extracts the email data, and then links the user and email records to make composite records containing all the selected data. This operation, termed a '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'join'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Join_(SQL)', 'webpage_id': 0}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', can be computationally expensive. Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-from_19-1'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[19]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-from-19', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': "In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records. Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the "}, {'_': 'TextFixed', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'userpk'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record. That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records. This can eliminate the costly join operations. For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records. A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together. For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-from_19-2'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[19]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-from-19', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep. For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code. In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users. In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'backlinks'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backlink', 'webpage_id': 5973540602495382073}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users. This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output. In terms of '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'big O notation'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation', 'webpage_id': 5973540601353486218}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', this query would be '}, {'_': 'TextImage', 'document_id': 5968513766881493463, 'w': 139, 'h': 24}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' time ‚Äì i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data. In contrast, the relational version would be multiple '}, {'_': 'TextImage', 'document_id': 5783928815667380324, 'w': 73, 'h': 24}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' lookups, plus the time needed to join all of the data records.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-from_19-3'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[19]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-from-19', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query. For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gone_with_the_Wind_(film)', 'webpage_id': 0}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '". This first requires the system to find the actors in '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', find all the movies they were in, find all the actors in all of those movies who were not the lead in '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', and then find all of the movies they were in, finally filtering that list to those with descriptions containing "submarine". In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results. In contrast, the graph database would walk from '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' to '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Clark Gable'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clark_Gable', 'webpage_id': 5973540602123825506}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies. The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine". All of this can be done via one search.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-examples_20-0'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[20]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-examples-20', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Properties'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' add another layer of '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'abstraction'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction_(computer_science)', 'webpage_id': 0}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' to this structure that also improves many common queries. Properties are essentially labels that can be applied to any record, or in some cases, edges as well. For example, one might label Clark Gable as "actor", which would then allow the system to quickly find all the records that are actors, as opposed to director or camera operator. If labels on edges are allowed, one could also label the relationship between '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' and Clark Gable as "lead", and by performing a search on people that are "lead" "actor" in the movie '}, {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Gone With the Wind'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', the database would produce '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Vivien Leigh'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vivien_Leigh', 'webpage_id': 5973540601818786896}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Olivia de Havilland'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olivia_de_Havilland', 'webpage_id': 5973540601494619878}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' and Clark Gable. The equivalent SQL query would have to rely on added data in the table linking people and movies, adding more complexity to the query syntax. These sorts of labels may improve search performance under certain circumstances, but are generally more useful in providing added semantic data for end users.'}, {'_': 'TextSuperscript', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'back_cite_ref-examples_20-1'}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '[20]'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_database#cite_note-examples-20', 'webpage_id': 0}]}}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data is one or two levels deep. For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query. Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links. They are especially well suited to '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'social networking'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_networking', 'webpage_id': 5973540602861414838}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded. Voxel ‚Äî –æ–±—Ä–∞–∑–æ–≤–∞–Ω–æ –∏–∑ —Å–ª–æ–≤: –æ–±—ä—ë–º–Ω—ã–π (–∞–Ω–≥–ª. volumetric) –∏ –ø–∏–∫—Å–µ–ª—å (–∞–Ω–≥–ª. pixel)) ‚Äî —ç–ª–µ–º–µ–Ω—Ç –æ–±—ä—ë–º–Ω–æ–≥–æ –∏–∑–æ–±—Ä–∞–∂–µ–Ω–∏—è, —Å–æ–¥–µ—Ä–∂–∞—â–∏–π –∑–Ω–∞—á–µ–Ω–∏–µ —ç–ª–µ–º–µ–Ω—Ç–∞ —Ä–∞—Å—Ç—Ä–∞ –≤ —Ç—Ä—ë—Ö–º–µ—Ä–Ω–æ–º –ø—Ä–æ—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω—Å—Ç–≤–µ. –í–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏ —è–≤–ª—è—é—Ç—Å—è –∞–Ω–∞–ª–æ–≥–∞–º–∏ –¥–≤—É–º–µ—Ä–Ω—ã—Ö –ø–∏–∫—Å–µ–ª–µ–π –¥–ª—è —Ç—Ä—ë—Ö–º–µ—Ä–Ω–æ–≥–æ –ø—Ä–æ—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω—Å—Ç–≤–∞. –í–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª—å–Ω—ã–µ –º–æ–¥–µ–ª–∏ —á–∞—Å—Ç–æ –∏—Å–ø–æ–ª—å–∑—É—é—Ç—Å—è –¥–ª—è –≤–∏–∑—É–∞–ª–∏–∑–∞—Ü–∏–∏ –∏ –∞–Ω–∞–ª–∏–∑–∞ –º–µ–¥–∏—Ü–∏–Ω—Å–∫–æ–π –∏ –Ω–∞—É—á–Ω–æ–π –∏–Ω—Ñ–æ—Ä–º–∞—Ü–∏–∏.

–í –∫–æ–º–ø—å—é—Ç–µ—Ä–Ω–æ–π –≥—Ä–∞—Ñ–∏–∫–µ –≤–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏ –∏—Å–ø–æ–ª—å–∑—É—é—Ç—Å—è –∫–∞–∫ –∞–ª—å—Ç–µ—Ä–Ω–∞—Ç–∏–≤–∞ –ø–æ–ª–∏–≥–æ–Ω–∞–º. –ù–æ–≤–∏—á–∫–∏ –∏–Ω–æ–≥–¥–∞ –æ—à–∏–±–æ—á–Ω–æ —Å—á–∏—Ç–∞—é—Ç –≤–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏ –∑–∞–º–µ–Ω–æ–π –¥–ª—è —Ñ–∏–∑–∏—á–µ—Å–∫–∏—Ö –ø–∏–∫—Å–µ–ª–µ–π (—ç–ª–µ–º–µ–Ω—Ç–æ–≤ –º–∞—Ç—Ä–∏—Ü—ã –¥–∏—Å–ø–ª–µ—è). –ù–∞ —Å–∞–º–æ–º –¥–µ–ª–µ –ø–æ–¥ –≤–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª–æ–º –æ–±—ã—á–Ω–æ –ø–æ–Ω–∏–º–∞–µ—Ç—Å—è –≤–∏—Ä—Ç—É–∞–ª—å–Ω—ã–π —ç–ª–µ–º–µ–Ω—Ç, —Å–æ–æ—Ç–≤–µ—Ç—Å—Ç–≤—É—é—â–∏–π –Ω–∞–±–æ—Ä—É –∏–∑ —à–µ—Å—Ç–∏ –ø—Ä—è–º–æ—É–≥–æ–ª—å–Ω—ã—Ö –ø–æ–ª–∏–≥–æ–Ω–æ–≤. –í—Å—ë –≤ –≤–∏—Ä—Ç—É–∞–ª—å–Ω–æ–º –º–∏—Ä–µ ‚Äî –≤–∏—Ä—Ç—É–∞–ª—å–Ω—ã–µ –ø–∏–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏, –ø–æ–ª–∏–≥–æ–Ω—ã –∏ –≤–æ–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏ ‚Äî –¥–æ–ª–∂–Ω–æ –±—ã—Ç—å —Å–ø—Ä–æ–µ—Ü–∏—Ä–æ–≤–∞–Ω–æ –Ω–∞ –ø–∏–∫—Å–µ–ª–∏ —Ñ–∏–∑–∏—á–µ—Å–∫–æ–≥–æ —ç–∫—Ä–∞–Ω–∞:[–∏—Å—Ç–æ—á–Ω–∏–∫ –Ω–µ —É–∫–∞–∑–∞–Ω 1072 –¥–Ω—è]

'blocks': [{'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The Girvan‚ÄìNewman algorithm detects communities by progressively removing edges from the original network. The connected components of the remaining network are the communities. Instead of trying to construct a measure that tells us which edges are the most central to communities, the Girvan‚ÄìNewman algorithm focuses on edges that are most likely "between" communities.'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Vertex betweenness'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betweenness_centrality', 'webpage_id': 5973540601331802335}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' is an indicator of highly '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'central'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centrality', 'webpage_id': 5973540601494088752}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' nodes in networks. For any node '}, {'_': 'TextImage', 'document_id': 5840543146122936435, 'w': 7, 'h': 19}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', vertex betweenness is defined as the fraction of shortest paths between pairs of nodes that run through it. It is relevant to models where the network modulates transfer of goods between known start and end points, under the assumption that such transfer seeks the shortest available route.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The Girvan‚ÄìNewman algorithm extends this definition to the case of edges, defining the "edge betweenness" of an edge as the number of shortest paths between pairs of nodes that run along it. If there is more than one shortest path between a pair of nodes, each path is assigned equal weight such that the total weight of all of the paths is equal to unity. If a network contains communities or groups that are only loosely connected by a few inter-group edges, then all shortest paths between different communities must go along one of these few edges. Thus, the edges connecting communities will have high edge betweenness (at least '}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'one'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' of them). By removing these edges, the groups are separated from one another and so the underlying community structure of the network is revealed.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': "The algorithm's steps for community detection are summarized below"}}, {'_': 'PageBlockOrderedList', 'items': [{'_': 'PageListOrderedItemText', 'num': '', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The betweenness of all existing edges in the network is calculated first.'}}, {'_': 'PageListOrderedItemText', 'num': '', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The edge(s) with the highest betweenness are removed.'}}, {'_': 'PageListOrderedItemText', 'num': '', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The betweenness of all edges affected by the removal is recalculated.'}}, {'_': 'PageListOrderedItemText', 'num': '', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Steps 2 and 3 are repeated until no edges remain.'}}]}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': "The fact that the only betweennesses being recalculated are only the ones which are affected by the removal, may lessen the running time of the process' simulation in computers. However, the betweenness centrality must be recalculated with each step, or severe errors occur. The reason is that the network adapts itself to the new conditions set after the edge removal. For instance, if two communities are connected by more than one edge, then there is no guarantee that "}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'all'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' of these edges will have high betweenness. According to the method, we know that '}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'at least one'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' of them will have, but nothing more than that is known. By recalculating betweennesses after the removal of each edge, it is ensured that at least one of the remaining edges between two communities will always have a high value.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The end result of the Girvan‚ÄìNewman algorithm is a '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'dendrogram'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dendrogram', 'webpage_id': 5973540602851947478}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '. As the Girvan‚ÄìNewman algorithm runs, the dendrogram is produced from the top down (i.e. the network splits up into different communities with the successive removal of links). The leaves of the dendrogram are individual nodes.'}]}}], 'title': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Edge betweenness and community structure'}, {'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'Edge_betweenness_and_community_structure'}]}, 'open': False}, {'_': 'PageBlockDetails', 'blocks': [{'_': 'PageBlockList', 'items': [{'_': 'PageListItemText', 'text': {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Closeness'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closeness_(mathematics)', 'webpage_id': 0}}, {'_': 'PageListItemText', 'text': {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Hierarchical clustering'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hierarchical_clustering', 'webpage_id': 5973540602912715725}}, {'_': 'PageListItemText', 'text': {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Modularity'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modularity_(networks)', 'webpage_id': 0}}]}], 'title': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'See also'}, {'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}, 'name': 'See_also'}]}, 'open': False}, {'_': 'PageBlockDetails', 'blocks': [{'_': 'PageBlockOrderedList', 'items': [{'_': 'PageListOrderedItemText', 'num': '', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '^'}, 'url': 'https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girvan%E2%80%93Newman_algorithm#back_cite_ref-newman_1-0', 'webpage_id': 0}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' '}, {'_': 'TextAnchor', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Girvan M. and Newman M. Using interventions you can determine the type of relationship between experience and income (causal or association), and in which direction it flows (experience causes income). You can think of '}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'interventions'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' as a way of answering certain types of ‚Äúwhat if‚Äù questions: What if I was 45, instead of 31, how much would I earn?'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Modern AI systems are very good at identifying associations in the data and these relationships are fundamental to their success. However, because these systems have traditionally been blind to causality, they have repeatedly learnt misleading associations from the data. These misleading associations, or '}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'spurious correlations'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', can be pernicious and dangerously harmful to AI systems.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Intuitively, a correlation is spurious when we do not expect it to hold in the future in the same way it held in the past. You can find a great list of spurious correlations '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'here'}, 'url': 'https://www.notion.so/A-6-Minute-Introduction-to-Causal-AI-423f7531c87244e8be874506e82060ca', 'webpage_id': 0}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': '. The elimination of spurious correlations is the basis of the randomised controlled trial; the scientific gold standard for proving a hypothesis.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Causal AI is powerful because it allows you to identify and eliminate spurious correlations using the existing observed data- without the need to run a controlled trial.'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockHeader', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Biased'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Spurious correlations are everywhere and are regularly learnt by modern AI systems. In order to ensure your model generates useful and safe predictions this bias needs to be controlled for.'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Causal techniques allow the creation of a '}, {'_': 'TextBold', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'causal diagram'}}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ' which shows the relationships between the variables. Each arrow within this diagram demonstrates how one variable causally impacts another, e.g. experience has a causal effect on income. This allows you to explicitly represent the biases within the data.'}]}}, {'_': 'PageBlockPhoto', 'photo_id': 5806401201707790071, 'caption': {'_': 'PageCaption', 'text': {'_': 'TextItalic', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Figure 2: Example of a simplified causal diagram mapping the relationships between the variables shown in Table 1 above.'}}, 'credit': {'_': 'TextEmpty'}}, 'url': None, 'webpage_id': None}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'Once you have a causal diagram which you believe accurately represents how the data are related to one another it can be manipulated to control for a range of different factors- including elimination of bias.'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'One manipulation could be an intervention on the sex of the German female engineer to see how that would impact their income. Alternatively, by '}, {'_': 'TextUrl', 'text': {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'controlling for sex'}, 'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controlling_for_a_variable', 'webpage_id': 3384953264636165637}, {'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': ', you can remove the influence of sex from the causal diagram. Causal models should be selected based upon criteria which test their stability to changing conditions, e.g. when interventions are performed. Scientists follow this mantra when performing controlled trials to identify causal relationships.'}}, {'_': 'PageBlockParagraph', 'text': {'_': 'TextConcat', 'texts': [{'_': 'TextPlain', 'text': 'The result is that causal models are more robust to changing conditions in the real world and can adapt more rapidly to dramatic shifts in the data. ‚Ä¢  –û–±–∞ –Ω–∞–±–ª—é–¥–∞—Ç–µ–ª—è –ø–æ–ª—É—á–∏–ª–∏ —Ä–∞–∑–Ω—ã–µ —Ä–µ–∑—É–ª—å—Ç–∞—Ç—ã –∏–∑–º–µ—Ä–µ–Ω–∏–π. –ò –æ–±–∞ –æ–Ω–∏ –≤–µ—Ä–Ω—ã, –ø–æ—Å–∫–æ–ª—å–∫—É –æ–Ω–∏ –∏—Å—Ö–æ–¥—è—Ç –∏–∑ —Ä–∞–∑–Ω—ã—Ö —Å–∏—Å—Ç–µ–º –æ—Ç—Å—á–µ—Ç–∞.
